HOUSE JOINT RESOLUTION 1650
By Cochran
A RESOLUTION to honor and commend the Community Action
Group of Englewood on the fortieth anniversary
of Englewood June Days.
WHEREAS, it is our pleasure to recognize those institutions that enrich communities,
serve as cultural touchstones, and contribute to the enduring legacy of the great cities that
comprise the Volunteer State; and
WHEREAS, one such organization is the Community Action Group of Englewood, which
will commemorate the fortieth anniversary of Englewood June Days in 2026, marking four
decades of honoring this State's rich and diverse heritage and culture; and
WHEREAS, with historic buildings lining Main Street, a silver water tower gracing the
skyline, and residents who knew each other by name, the Town of Englewood embodied all the
quintessential charms of small-town America, except for one thing: an annual festival; and
WHEREAS, that missing piece finally fell into place in 1986, when communities across
Tennessee organized celebrations and festivals in honor of Tennessee Homecoming '86; and
WHEREAS, according to the University of Tennessee's Special Collections, the
Homecoming '86 initiative was designed to give "Tennesseans an opportunity to rediscover their
past, identify the uniqueness of their own communities, and invite other Tennesseans to
celebrate with them"; and
WHEREAS, in partnership with the statewide initiative, Englewood Mayor Bob Middleton
appointed Marion Cochran, a retired local school teacher, to chair the Homecoming '86
Planning Committee; Mrs. Cochran assembled a group of Englewood residents and organized a
celebration in late June, featuring softball games, class reunions, and a banquet for former
Englewood High School students; and
