- 1 -

WHEREAS, the week's events culminated with a grand festival on Saturday, followed by
a community-wide church service on Sunday; the festival featured a pancake breakfast,
bluegrass and country music, arts and crafts exhibits, and a square dance on Main Street; and
WHEREAS, Tennessee Homecoming '86 proved a resounding success in Englewood,
drawing hundreds of former and current residents who gathered to celebrate their town's rich
heritage and savor the fellowship of old friends; and
WHEREAS, due to the overwhelmingly positive response, the Homecoming Planning
Committee saw no reason for the celebration to end after one year, so when the last weekend
of June 1987 rolled around, the citizens of Englewood gathered once again to hold their newly
established annual festival, June Days; and
WHEREAS, nearly four decades since Homecoming '86, the celebration endures in
Englewood; although some still affectionately call the festival June Days, it is now often called
Englewood Celebrates, and it proudly stands as one of the last surviving Homecoming '86
events; and
WHEREAS, the Homecoming '86 Planning Committee eventually became the charter
members of a local nonprofit organization known as the Community Action Group of
Englewood, commonly referred to as CAGE; and
WHEREAS, today, CAGE is headquartered in historic Downtown Englewood, and the
organization continues its mission of preserving and promoting Englewood's unique heritage
through the operation of the Englewood Textile and History Museum and numerous community
events, such as Englewood Celebrates, that it organizes each year; and
WHEREAS, staying true to its roots, Englewood Celebrates closely resembles the
festival begun nearly forty years ago; pancakes are still served on Saturday morning as the
sound of local bluegrass wafts through the town streets, and come sundown, Main Street closes
to traffic as hundreds flock to Downtown Englewood for the evening dance; and
- 2 - 018684

WHEREAS, Englewood Celebrates also boasts new attractions, including a motorcycle
show and poker run, an antique tractor show, and numerous food and craft vendors; and
WHEREAS, community pride is palpable in Englewood; it has been prominently on
display for four decades now through a homecoming celebration that has become a tradition
and a small group of active citizens who have become a safeguard of local heritage; and
WHEREAS, it is most fitting that we recognize CAGE and Englewood June Days on this
most auspicious occasion; now, therefore,
BE IT RESOLVED BY THE HOUSE OF REPRESENTATIVES OF THE ONE HUNDRED
FOURTEENTH GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF THE STATE OF TENNESSEE, THE SENATE
CONCURRING, that we honor and commend the Community Action Group of Englewood on
the fortieth anniversary of Englewood June Days, extending our sincere gratitude for the good
work of this organization and our best wishes for its continued success in the future.
BE IT FURTHER RESOLVED, that an appropriate copy of this resolution be prepared
for presentation with this final clause omitted from such copy and upon proper request made to
the appropriate clerk, the language appearing immediately following the State seal appear
without House or Senate designation.
